      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Lead Paint in Older Brisbane Homes: What Sellers Need to Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Brisbane's significant stock of pre-1970 Queenslanders and post-war homes means many properties on the market today may contain lead paint. Here is what you need to know before you list.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Lead paint is not a topic that comes up in most property conversations, but for sellers of older Brisbane homes it deserves careful attention. Paint containing lead was used routinely in Australian homes built before 1970, and was sometimes used in homes built right up to 1997, when it was finally phased out of Australian residential construction. Given Brisbane's large stock of pre-war and post-war homes, particularly Queenslanders and fibro cottages across the inner east, a significant number of properties coming to market today may have some lead paint present.</p>

      <p>The good news is that lead paint in sound, intact condition poses minimal risk to occupants and does not, by itself, prevent a successful sale. The problems arise when paint deteriorates, is disturbed by renovation work, or is improperly removed. Understanding where it is typically found, what your disclosure obligations actually are, and how to handle it sensibly before you list is what separates sellers who manage this issue cleanly from those who find it becoming a negotiation problem mid-campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Where lead paint is typically found</h2>
      <p>In older Brisbane homes, lead paint is most commonly found on exterior surfaces: weatherboards, window frames, doors, fascias, and gutters. Interior surfaces where it appears regularly include skirting boards, door frames, cornices, and older built-in joinery. In many homes that have been repainted over the decades, the lead paint is buried under several layers of more recent paint. As long as those layers remain intact and in good condition, the lead paint below them is effectively contained.</p>

      <p>The risk increases significantly when that upper layer starts to fail. Peeling, flaking, and chalking exterior paint on a pre-1970 home is worth taking seriously, both because it is a health hazard if there are children or vulnerable occupants in the home, and because it will attract scrutiny from building inspectors and buyers who are attuned to the age of the property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What Queensland law requires of sellers</h2>
      <p>There is no Queensland legislation that requires sellers to test for lead paint before listing. You are not obligated to commission a lead paint assessment as a condition of sale. This is different from the requirements that apply to landlords undertaking renovation work in older homes, or to parents of children with elevated blood lead levels.</p>

      <p>Where disclosure does become legally relevant is under the material facts obligations that apply to all Queensland property sales. If you know that lead paint is present and that it is in a deteriorating condition, that is likely a material fact. Deteriorated lead paint is a health risk, and concealing a known health risk from a buyer creates exposure to claims after settlement. If you have had a lead paint test done and it came back positive, that result should be disclosed rather than ignored.</p>

      <p>The practical boundary is this: if you have no specific knowledge of lead paint in your home, and the paintwork appears intact, you are not required to go looking for it before you sell. If you do have knowledge, deal with it openly. Buyers and their solicitors in Brisbane are increasingly asking about lead paint in older homes, and an honest answer costs you far less than an undisclosed problem discovered after settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers and their inspectors look for</h2>
      <p>Building inspectors in Brisbane do not routinely test for lead paint as part of a standard building inspection report. Lead paint testing requires specialist equipment and is typically only carried out when specifically instructed. However, a building inspector will flag deteriorated paintwork, peeling exterior paint, and visible paint failure, particularly on older timber homes. A buyer who reads that report and is aware of the home's age will often ask the question.</p>

      <p>Buyers in the market for an older Queenslander or post-war home are, as a group, more informed about lead paint than they were a decade ago. Renovation-active buyers in particular, who plan to do significant work after purchase, are likely to factor lead paint management costs into their thinking and may raise it as a negotiation point if they find evidence of deteriorated paint during inspections.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Renovating before sale: the right approach for pre-1970 homes</h2>
      <p>If you are planning to do any renovation or remediation work on a pre-1970 Brisbane home before listing, this is where lead paint management matters most. Sanding, grinding, or pressure-washing lead-painted surfaces without appropriate precautions creates significant risk: to occupants, to your contractors, and to neighbours. It also creates a legal and contractual risk if you sell the home after those works and a buyer later discovers improper lead removal.</p>

      <p>For any renovation work on surfaces that may contain lead paint in a pre-1970 home, engage a licensed lead-safe renovation contractor. This is not a niche request: there are a number of painting and renovation businesses in Brisbane with the relevant licences and equipment. When the work is done, obtain a clearance report. Keep that documentation and disclose it to buyers as part of your pre-sale information. It converts what might otherwise be a buyer concern into a positive: evidence that the issue was identified, managed professionally, and documented.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical advice for sellers</h2>
      <p>If your home is pre-1970 and the exterior paintwork is original or visibly deteriorated, get a visual assessment done before you go to market. You do not necessarily need a full lead paint swab test in every room: a targeted assessment of the surfaces most likely to cause concern, particularly exterior weatherboards, window frames, and doors, is usually sufficient to inform your decision-making. If the paint is intact and in reasonable condition, that assessment gives you confidence to proceed. If it is not, you have time to address it before buyers and their inspectors are walking through the property.</p>

      <p>For homes that have been repainted in the last decade with no visible deterioration of the paintwork underneath, lead paint is unlikely to present as a campaign issue. The risk profile is much higher in properties with aging exterior paint, visible chalking or flaking, or a history of extended periods without maintenance.</p>

      <p>The broader principle is that buyers in Brisbane's inner east are buying older homes knowing they come with older-home characteristics. Lead paint in good condition is one of those characteristics. Managing it professionally and disclosing what you know gives buyers the information they need and removes the ambiguity that creates negotiation leverage in the wrong direction.</p>

